      <bioghist id="aspace_0c1d3f5a6e85133e01122f0f589b0200">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Traugott Lawler received his B.A. from College of the Holy Cross in 1958, an M.A. from University of Wisconsin in 1962, and a Ph.D. from Harvard University in 1966. He was a member of the Yale faculty from 1966 to 1972, taught at Northwestern University from 1972 to 1982, and returned to Yale in 1981.</p>
         <p>In 1981, Lawlor and Ralph Hanna were asked to take over a project on the sources of the "Book of Wikked Wyves" mentioned by the Wife of Bath in the <title>
               <part>Canterbury Tales</part>
            </title>.  Originally begun by Yale Professor Karl Young (1879-1943) in the 1930s, the work was continued by his student, Robert Armstrong Pratt (1907-1987). The notes, microfilm and other research materials collected by Young and Pratt were divided between Hanna and Lawler and served as the basis for the two volume set of <title>
               <part>Jankyn's Book of Wikked Wyves,</part>
            </title>, with volume one, <title>
               <part>The Primary Texts</part>
            </title>, published in 1997 and volume 2, <title>
               <part>Seven Commentaries on Walter Map's "Dissuasio Valerii"</part>
            </title>, published in 2014.</p>
         <p>A medievalist scholar and an expert on William Langland, his other published works include <title>
               <part>The One and the Many in the Canterbury Tales</part>
            </title> and <title>
               <part>The Parisiana Poetria of John of Garland</part>
            </title>, as well as numerous journal articles. After his retirement from Yale in 2005, Lawlor continued his academic work as emeritus professor of English.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_c84be7440ba205a1320af31fc7ea133d">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>This collection consists of material related to a two volume set of <title>
               <part>Jankyn's Book of Wikked Wyves</part>
            </title>, edited by Ralph Hanna III and Traugott Lawler as part of the Modern Language Association's Chaucer Library Series. In the first volume, Hanna and Lawler presented comprehensive versions of the three medieval texts that comprised Jankyn's "Book of Wikked Wives" which is referenced in "The Wife of Bath's Tale" in <title>
               <part>The Canterbury Tales</part>
            </title>. In the second volume, Hanna and Lawler presented the known contemporary commentaries on one of the three texts, Walter Map's "Dissuasio Valerii," or "The Letter of Valerius to His Friend Ruffinus, Dissuading Him from Marrying." The bulk of the material consists of transcriptions, translations, glosses and reproductions of portions of the commentaries, which were used during the production of volume two. It includes some material not in the published work. The collection also includes drafts of volume one and correspondence related to the project.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
